{{short description|Complex number that is a root of a non-zero polynomial in one variable with rational coefficients}}
{{Distinguish|Algebraic solution}}
[[File:Square root of 2 triangle.svg|thumb|200px|The square root of 2 is an algebraic number equal to the length of the [[hypotenuse]] of a [[right triangle]] with legs of length 1]]

An '''algebraic number''' is any [[complex number]] (including [[real number]]s) that is a [[root of a function|root]] of a non-zero [[polynomial]] (that is, a value which causes the polynomial to equal 0) in one variable with [[rational number|rational]] coefficients (or equivalently – by [[clearing denominators]] – with [[integer]] coefficients). All integers and rational numbers are algebraic, as are all [[nth root|roots of integers]]. There are real and complex numbers that are not algebraic, such as [[Pi|{{pi}}]] and [[e (mathematical constant)|{{mvar|e}}]]. These numbers are called [[transcendental number]]s. While the set of complex numbers is [[uncountable set|uncountable]], the set of algebraic numbers is [[countable set|countable]] and has [[measure zero]] in the [[Lebesgue measure]] as a subset of the complex numbers, and in this sense [[almost all]] complex numbers are transcendental.

